AGI - The United States reached separate agreements on Tuesday at Riad with Ukraine and Russia to stop fighting in the Black Sea and suspend attacks against energy objectives, with Washington agreeing to contribute to the loosening of some sanctions against Moscow.
&nbsp;
This is a point of potential new frictions between Washington and Brussels. The White House never appoints it in these terms, but the understanding closed in Saudi Arabia follows the so-called Black Sea Initiative, signed in 2022 with the mediation of Turkey and Onu. It is the agreement that has helped Ukraine to market its cereals and other safe agricultural products, while at the same time allowing inspections of ships in the Black Sea, to prevent them from being used for the supply of weapons. Kiev complained that Russia was using inspections to block its export, accusations that Moscow has always denied.
&nbsp;
For Russia, the Black Sea Intesa includes crucially many of the conditions of a three-year Memorandum of Understanding accompanying the document, under which UN officials agreed to help Moscow bring its agricultural and fertilizer products to foreign markets. Russian President Vladimir Putin complained that the West never removed obstacles to Russian grain exports.
&nbsp;
For this reason, in 2023, the Kremlin came out unilaterally from the Black Sea Initiative. "This time justice must prevail," said Putin's spokesman, Dmitri Peskov, commenting on the fate of the understanding that in fact repels the Black Sea Initiative.
&nbsp;
While Russian exports of food and fertilizers are not subject to Western sanctions - also because prohibited by international law - Moscow has denounced that restrictions on payments, logistics and insurance have represented an obstacle to its export in this sector. Moscow now asks that the Russian state bank that deals with the food industry, Rosselkhozbank, is reconnected to Swift and has allowed other banks to have access to the international payment system again.
&nbsp;
This and other steps may require the agreement of European countries that do not seem favorable. Despite its claims, Russia remains the world's leading exporter of wheat and fertilizers: the agency Reuters previews that Russia will send about 40 million tons of grain to the global markets this season, mainly to traditional customers in the Middle East and aims to increase its total agricultural exports by 50% by 2030.
&nbsp;
"The ultimate end of Putin is clear: wants Trump to revoke sanctions to Russian banks and energy companies to allow the Kremlin to draw on the strong currency he desperately needs," said Edward Fishman, researcher at Columbia University and former senior official for US sanctions, interviewed by the Wall Street Journal.&nbsp;
